<typeStatus id="54C46B97CE4FBA56511B831625844864" box="[870,974,1028,1052]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="1344C9B0CE4FBA5651A38316227F4865" box="[990,1077,1028,1053]" captionStart="Figures 22–28" captionStartId="28.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figures 22–28. Adetus spp. 22–27) Adetus x-fasciatus sp. nov.: 22) Dorsal habitus, holotype male. 23) Ventral habitus, holotype male. 24) Lateral habitus, holotype male. 25) Head, frontal view, holotype male. 26) Dorsal habitus, paratype female. 27) Ventral habitus, paratype female. 28) Adetus pusillus, holotype, dorsal habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677219" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677219/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). A single specimen identified as 
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA56529D8337272B4845" baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[224,353,1061,1085]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA56529D8337272B4845" box="[224,353,1061,1085]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the MZSP collection (
<figureCitation id="1344C9B0CE4FBA5650FE833725494845" box="[643,771,1061,1085]" captionStart="Figures 22–28" captionStartId="28.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figures 22–28. Adetus spp. 22–27) Adetus x-fasciatus sp. nov.: 22) Dorsal habitus, holotype male. 23) Ventral habitus, holotype male. 24) Lateral habitus, holotype male. 25) Head, frontal view, holotype male. 26) Dorsal habitus, paratype female. 27) Ventral habitus, paratype female. 28) Adetus pusillus, holotype, dorsal habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677219" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677219/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 22–25</figureCitation>
) differs notably from that species (by the general shape, prothoracic shape, pubescence, punctation, etc.) and is an example of the new species 
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5656AF8357233C4825" box="[1234,1398,1093,1117]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. In 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEEA8C4CE4FBA565360837427804806" author="Bezark" box="[285,458,1126,1150]" firstAuthor="Bezark" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" refId="ref19378" refString="Bezark, L. G. 2019. A photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the New World. Available at https: // apps 2. cdfa. ca. gov / publicApps / plant / bycidDB / wsearch. asp? w = n. (Last accessed February 2019.)" type="url" year="2019">Bezark (2019)</bibRefCitation>
, there is another specimen identified as 
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA5651C4837422764806" baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[953,1084,1126,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5651C4837422764806" box="[953,1084,1126,1150]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that is also 
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5656AC8374233C4806" box="[1233,1398,1126,1150]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. This latter specimen is from 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA565029839424DF48E6" box="[596,661,1158,1182]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
(“ 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA5650CD8394249748E6" box="[688,733,1158,1182]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Isla</collectingCountry>
de Ozo”) and belonged to the MNRJ collection. That speci- men was destroyed in the fire that completely consumed the MNRJ in 2018. Thus, it is not possible to include it as a 
<typeStatus id="54C46B97CE4FBA56530C83DA27A84898" box="[369,482,1224,1248]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">paratype</typeStatus>
. Furthermore, we were not able to find any place in 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA56562683D522D648A7" box="[1115,1180,1223,1247]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
named “ 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA56577583D5237F48A7" box="[1288,1333,1223,1247]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Isla</collectingCountry>
de Ozo.” For this reason, we consider it doubtful that 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA56509E83FA256E4978" box="[739,804,1256,1280]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
is a country where 
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA56566883FA22F34978" box="[1045,1209,1256,1280]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. occurs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC0D535CE4FBA565295821A25BC49F9" blockId="9.[192,1441,996,1605]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<bibRefCitation id="EFEEA8C4CE4FBA565295821A24694958" author="Zajciw, D. &amp; M. A. Monne" box="[232,547,1288,1313]" journalOrPublisher="Revista de la Sociedad Uruguaya de Entomologia" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="51 - 61" part="7" refId="ref22189" refString="Zajciw, D., and M. A. Monne. 1968. Cerambicidos del Uruguay, nuevos o poco conocidos. Revista de la Sociedad Uruguaya de Entomologia 7: 51 - 61." title="Cerambicidos del Uruguay, nuevos o poco conocidos" type="journal article" year="1968">Zajciw and Monné (1968)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA5650DD821A256C4958" baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[672,806,1288,1312]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5650DD821A256C4958" box="[672,806,1288,1312]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA565127821B258D4959" box="[858,967,1289,1313]" name="Uruguay" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
and reported (translated): “Described from 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA56537C823B270F4939" box="[257,325,1321,1345]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
, subsequently recorded by Bruch for 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA565172823B25304938" box="[783,890,1321,1344]" name="Taiwan" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Formosa</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA5651F7823B22414939" box="[906,1035,1321,1345]" name="Argentina" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Argentina</collectingCountry>
). Very interesting finding for the country’s fauna.” Unfortunately, it is not possible to check if the records of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA565631825B22854919" baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[1100,1231,1353,1377]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA565631825B22854919" box="[1100,1231,1353,1377]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA56568382582321491A" box="[1278,1387,1354,1378]" name="Uruguay" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA5652BD8278277649FA" box="[192,316,1386,1410]" name="Argentina" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry id="F36895A5CE4FBA565331827827F249FA" box="[332,440,1386,1410]" name="Taiwan" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Formosa</collectingCountry>
) were really based on specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA565110827825BA49FA" baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[877,1008,1386,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA565110827825BA49FA" box="[877,1008,1386,1410]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC0D535CE4FBA565295829825074A3D" blockId="9.[192,1441,996,1605]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5652958298278349DA" box="[232,457,1418,1442]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA5652958298277649DA" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1852" box="[232,316,1418,1442]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Adetus</taxonomicName>
x-fasciatus
</emphasis>
sp. nov. resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA5650BF829822E749DB" authority="Breuning, 1971" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1971" box="[706,1197,1418,1443]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atomarius" subSpecies="invittatus">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5650BF829825AE49DA" box="[706,996,1418,1442]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. atomarius invittatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEEA8C4CE4FBA565190829822E749DB" author="Breuning" box="[1005,1197,1418,1443]" firstAuthor="Breuning" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="209 - 335" refId="ref19613" refString="Breuning, S. 1971. Revision des especes americaines de la tribue des Apomecynini Lac. (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomologische Abhandlungen aus dem Staatliches Museum fur Tierkunde 37 (3): 209 - 335." type="journal article" year="1971">Breuning, 1971</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by its light-colored dorsal pattern but it differs as follows: 
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5650E282B9250E49BB" box="[671,836,1451,1475]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. with central subcircular pubescent band of the elytra wide, well-marked and contiguous throughout; in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7FAEB6CE4FBA5651CA82D92298499B" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1971" box="[951,1234,1483,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atomarius" subSpecies="invittatus">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5651CA82D92298499B" box="[951,1234,1483,1507]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. atomarius invittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this band is narrower (or almost absent) with the distal portion more lateral, typically smaller and separated from the apical portion; in the former the lateral pubescent band at distal third is wide, in the latter species it is narrow and often reduced to a small, irregular fascia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36586BECE4FBA5652BD814F22624A0D" box="[192,1064,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC0D535CE4FBA5652BD814F22624A0D" blockId="9.[192,1064,1629,1653]" box="[192,1064,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B90B0927CE4FBA5652BD814F27114A0D" bold="true" box="[192,347,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for the light colored, x-shaped fascia on the elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
